  • Deprecated Classes 
    Class and Description
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.account.AccountRecordsQuery
    the result type of CryptoGetAccountRecordsResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to List<TransactionRecord>, which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.account.AccountStakersQuery
    the result type of CryptoGetStakersResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to a new type, which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.CallParams
    Moved to ContractFunctionParams. Note that some methods renamed for clarity and some less-used methods have been removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.CallParams.FunctionSelector
    Moved to ContractFunctionSelector.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.account.Claim
    for removal
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.contract.ContractBytecodeQuery
    the result type of ContractGetBytecodeResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to byte[], which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.contract.ContractCallQuery
    the result type of FunctionResult returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to ContractFunctionResult, which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.contract.ContractRecordsQuery
    the result type of ContractGetRecordsResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to List<TransactionRecord>, which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.crypto.ed25519.Ed25519Signature
    this class is being hidden in 1.0 because it was not intended for general use.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.file.FileContentsQuery
    the result type of FileGetContentsResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to byte[], which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.FunctionResult
    renamed to ContractFunctionResult. Note that some methods renamed for clarity and some less-used methods have been removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.GetBySolidityIdQuery
    the result type of GetBySolidityIDResponse returned from the various execute[Async](...) methods is changing in 1.0 to a new class, which is a breaking change. This class is not being removed.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.TransactionRecord.Transfer
    this class is being hoisted to a top level class in 1.0.

    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.Client.createAccount(PublicKey, long)
    hides useful configuration parameters for accounts and makes it difficult to handle errors properly; if an error occurs while fetching the receipt for the AccountCreateTransaction then the transaction ID is lost.

    You should build and execute your own AccountCreateTransaction instead.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.Client.createAccountAsync(PublicKey, long, Consumer<AccountId>, Consumer<HederaThrowable>)
    hides useful configuration parameters for accounts and makes it difficult to handle errors properly; if an error occurs while fetching the receipt for the AccountCreateTransaction then the transaction ID is lost.

    You should build and execute your own AccountCreateTransaction instead.

    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.Transaction.executeForReceipt()
    Makes it difficult to discern whether an error occurred while executing or while fetching a receipt. Call HederaCall.execute(Client) then Transaction.getReceipt(Client) and handle the errors separately from each.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.TransactionBuilder.executeForReceipt()
    Makes it difficult to discern whether an error occurred while executing or while fetching a receipt. If an error occurs while fetching the receipt then the transaction ID is difficult to retrieve.

    Call HederaCall.execute(Client) then TransactionId.getReceipt(Client) and handle the errors separately from each.

    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.Client.transferCryptoToAsync(AccountId, long, Consumer<TransactionId>, Consumer<HederaThrowable>)
    difficult to overload for multi-party transfers; additionally, if an error occurs while fetching the receipt for the CryptoTransferTransaction then the transaction ID is lost.

    You should build and execute your own CryptoTransferTransaction instead.
    com.hedera.hashgraph.sdk.HederaCall.validate()
    this method is being removed because it has limited utility for users; most implementations cannot guarantee that passing validation means the transaction or query will always succeed, so the method name is misleading at best.
